SIMPLE: imputation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Imputation
<hw>Im`pu*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <ety>[L. <ets>imputatio</ets> an
account, a charge: cf. F. <ets>imputation</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of imputing or charging; attribution;
ascription; also, anything imputed or charged.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qpers>Shylock</qpers>. Antonio is a good man.⟦br⟧
<qpers>Bassanio</qpers>. Have you heard any <qex>imputation</qex> to the
contrary?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If I had a suit to Master Shallow, I would humor his men with the
<qex>imputation</qex> of being near their master.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Charge or attribution of evil; censure; reproach;
insinuation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let us be careful to guard ourselves against these groundless
<qex>imputation</qex> of our enemies.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Theol.)</fld> <def>A setting of something to the
account of; the attribution of personal guilt or personal righteousness
of another; <as>as, the <ex>imputation</ex> of the sin of Adam, or the
righteousness of Christ</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Opinion; intimation; hint.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Imputative</ent>⟦br⟧
